    ABSTRACT: THE THERMAL HETERODYNE CHALLENGE
    The scalability of Photonic Interferometric Computing (PIC) is fundamentally limited by phase decoherence. In a large-scale N x N Mach-Zehnder Interferometer (MZI) mesh, even a millikelvin temperature shift (delta_T) induces a refractive index change (dn/dT) that causes phase-rotational errors. This document specifies the "Singing Machine," a proprietary architectural framework for real-time phase-drift compensation using spectral heterodyne monitoring and a multi-stage PID feedback loop.
    SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE: THE RESONANT CONTROL PLANE
    The Singing Machine operates as a "Control Plane" layered above the "Compute Plane" (the MZI mesh). It treats the entire photonic circuit as a tuned resonant cavity.

2.1. Pilot Tone Injection (Spectral Reference)
The system injects a coherent "Reference Pilot Tone" (lambda_ref) at a wavelength slightly offset from the data carrier (lambda_data). This reference signal traverses the same waveguide geometry as the data, thus experiencing identical thermal-optic perturbations.
2.2. In-Situ Optical Sampling
At every 10th junction in a Clements/Reck topology, a 1% tap-coupler diverts a fraction of the power to an Integrated Germanium (Ge) Photodetector (PD). These PDs monitor the "Interference State" of the pilot tone.

    THE PHYSICS OF THE SINGING MACHINE (MATHEMATICAL MODEL)

3.1. The Refractive Index Perturbation (dn/dT)
In silicon-on-insulator (SOI) waveguides, the effective refractive index (n_eff) is:
n_eff(T) = n_0 + (dn/dT) * (T - T_0)
For silicon, dn/dT is approximately 1.8 x 10^-4 K^-1.
3.2. Phase Error Equation (Epsilon)
The phase shift (phi) in an MZI arm of length L is:
phi = (2 * pi / lambda) * n_eff * L
The Singing Machine detects the error epsilon(t):
epsilon(t) = |phi_target - phi_measured(t)|
3.3. Heterodyne Beat Detection
By comparing the reference tone with a local oscillator on-chip, the system detects a "Beat Frequency" (f_beat). Any shift in f_beat indicates a phase drift. This is why the system is called the "Singing Machine" – it "listens" to the frequency shift of the light.

    THE "TRIPLE-GAIN" COMPENSATION ENGINE (PID)

The Singing Machine utilizes a high-speed PID (Proportional-Integral-Derivative) controller implemented in the CMOS-layer (bonded to the photonic die).
4.1. The Control Equation
The correction power (P_corr) applied to the Ti/Au micro-heaters is:
P_corr(t) = K_p * e(t) + K_i * Integral[e(tau) dtau] + K_d * (de/dt)

    Proportional (K_p): Corrects for immediate, low-amplitude thermal drift.
    Integral (K_i): Accumulates and eliminates steady-state errors caused by the chip's ambient operating temperature.
    Derivative (K_d): Counteracts rapid "Thermal Spikes" caused by high-density data bursts in adjacent waveguides (Crosstalk Compensation).

    HARMONIC CONSONANCE AND GLOBAL LOCKING

5.1. Unitary Matrix Stability
In a programmable photonic mesh, the global transfer matrix (M) must remain Unitary (M*M^H = I). Phase drift destroys unitarity. The Singing Machine maintains the "Consonant State" where:
Sum[ (M_ij_measured - M_ij_target)^2 ] < Sigma_noise
5.2. Adaptive Gradient Descent (AGD)
In addition to PID, the Singing Machine utilizes a low-frequency "Dither Signal" to perform on-chip gradient descent, finding the global "Phase Minimum" across thousands of MZIs simultaneously.

    HARDWARE SPECIFICATIONS (TARGET 2026)

    Sampling Rate: 100 MHz to 1 GHz (depending on thermal mass of the waveguide).
    Phase Precision: < 0.001 pi radians (Equivalent to 12-bit DAC precision).
    Power Overhead: < 5% of total chip power consumption.
    Latency: Sub-nanosecond response time for the Electro-Optic (EO) phase-shifters.

